When we first moved to LA in 2011, we lived right down the street from @farmersmarketla and have been coming here as a go-to for gifts, snacks, souvenirs and everything in between ever since! To prep for Mother’s Day coming up, I wanted to highlight some of my fave shops at this iconic L.A. landmark (with a little help from a certain someone ☺️) and show you some of the fun things we got for Kelly this year!

🍭 Dylan’s Candy Bar—chocolate-covered everything, always is the Mindell way. We made our own custom bag to go! 

🍫 Littlejohn’s—you can’t walk by this shop without sampling their famous English toffee. We got a gift box (that we 100% opened already. Quality control, people!)

🕯️ By Candlelight—We keep candles in nearly every room of our home so this was an easy one. Arlo picked out a white cypress scent that he said reminded him “of Christmas”. I know it’s only May. Just go with it.

🥐 Michelina—If you know my wife, you know that quality baked goods are the way to her heart. Had to make a stop here and pick up a few croissants and brioche loaves.

✨ Weiss Jewelry—Sara helped me pick out the most beautiful handmade ring that she and her husband Daniel crafted right there in their shop. Kelly loves simple, understated pieces so this yellow gold band with pavé diamonds will be a really cool addition to her ring stack!

Have you visited any of these vendors?! There are close to 100 🤯 // Next time you’re in LA, definitely swing by The Original Farmers Market!

I’m honestly not sure I’ll ever top this in terms of a memorable (personal) fan highlight, but without further ado, please run do not walk as I get to take you inside Walt Disney’s Storybook Mansion!!!!!! 🥹✨✨✨

Some quick background: I saw last week that Walt’s original home here in LA recently listed for rent and the news was blowing up everywhere from @archdigest to @LATimes to the @wsj. I had always driven by the home, but obviously never got to step inside—until now 😱😱😱

Enter my buddy @chasecampen. Chase and his family are truly some of the kindest people I was fortunate enough to work with at my last job before I went freelance. We’ve kept in touch over the years and I didn’t even realize that he was the very listing agent on this magical home until I scoped the MLS. It’s no secret at this point our family’s deep-rooted love and connection to Disney and I nearly fell over when Chase reached out and invited me to come check out the house. I brought Kelly with me and from the moment we stepped through the front door, it was just goosebumps.

In 1932, Disney purchased this undeveloped piece of property in Los Feliz and worked with architect Frank Crowhurst to custom design and build this very home where he lived with his wife Lillian and their two daughters, Diane and Sharon until 1950 (peep the little cottage at the end of the video where his kids used to play outside!) 🏠  

While in this house, Disney’s career included the release of Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs, Pinocchio, Fantasia, Dumbo, Bambi, The Adventures of Ichabod and Mr. Toad, and also a tiny film you’ve never of called Cinderella. And fun fact—even though Sleeping Beauty was not released until 1959, creative around the film (and the character of Maleficent), also happened in this house!

It’s not my shortest home tour by any means, but I really hope you sit back and enjoy all the magic little details. Huge thank you again to Chase for having us! 🙏🏼🏰♥️✨ #jminteriorspaces

This is something I honestly never thought I would be typing out and went back and forth about sharing this here, but one of my best friends of the past 15 years is currently on life-support. 

Days after bringing her beautiful new daughter Zoey into the world this past week, Mel began to experience critical complications. After going into severe septic shock on June 22nd and facing vital organ failure, she was put on ECMO to allow her body a chance to fight back.

We’re all having an unimaginably hard time wrapping our heads around these past few days and could use every last positive thought and prayer from the universe as one of the closest people in my life is fighting for hers.

If you can, please consider donating any amount you are able to at the link in my Story. All funds raised will be used exclusively for Mel’s medical expenses, childcare support, and essential household needs. And please keep Mel’s husband Nick, their two beautiful girls and their entire family in your hearts in the coming days, weeks, and months ahead. ♥️🙏🏼

Without exaggeration, I think one of the coolest things we’ve *ever* done as a family was this Mojigangas class we took with the famed Mexican artist @arroyo.hermes here in San Miguel. We learned all about the history of the giant Mojiganga puppets in Mexico, something Hermes is widely known for. He sat with us for over three hours and helped us create our very own customized mojiganga puppets! We painted on our outfits and Hermes hand-painted our faces, all the while sharing with us the most incredible stories from his past 30+ years as an artist—even being invited to the Vatican to meet the Pope!

An experience I won’t ever forget, thank you so much again Hermes for taking the time, sharing your love of the craft (and being so patient with the three of us! 👋🏼😂) #mindellsdomexico

🎥: @jeffmindell It’s the Walt Disney Studio Centennial! 💯 With Lillian expecting, in 1932 the Disneys moved into what’s now known as the Storybook Mansion - a 6,400 square-foot house at 4053 Woking Way in the Los Feliz hills. Though they sadly lost their first child, the couple soon welcomed two daughters - Diane was born in 1933, and they adopted Sharon in 1936. The family’s time at Woking Way coincided with an astounding run of theatrical releases for the Walt Disney Studio - the “Golden Age of Animation” between Snow White (1937) and Bambi (1942). Designed by Frank Crowhurst, the four-bedroom, five-bathroom estate features views of the LA skyline, a two-story living room, 10-car garage and a miniature playhouse for the daughters. Walt watched dailies of his productions in the home theater on the first floor. The Disneys lived at Woking Way until 1950, when they moved to Holmby Hills. Link in bio for all things Disney in LA! 😍 #discoverLA

It’s kind of fitting and awesome and perfect that the skies over CDMX decided to light up for such a visual sunset on our last night here in the city (pretty much every other evening, it has either been cloudy or drizzling at this time of the day.) Not tonight though…

I left Kelly and Arlo down in our room and decided to come up to the roof here at @circulomexicano for a cocktail and 20 minutes of quiet time. Ordered myself a margarita, sat down in a lounger (and was pretty much just scrolling through the pictures I had taken earlier today on my phone) when all of a sudden, I noticed that legitimately everything around me was just GLOWING pink. I’m not exaggerating when I say it was like out of a movie: everyone else at the bar, wait staff included, had already gotten up and was standing and looking at this incredible sunset. I took a few photos along with a couple video clips (swipe) just before the sky went dark again, and it started to rain. 

I couldn’t have asked for a more perfect way to wrap up this incredible trip. 🌅🇲🇽

Come with me inside the famed Morse House in Palm Springs!! ☀️🌵

This insane property was commissioned in 1961 by Hal Levitt for The Morses, a Chicago couple, who wanted a “Hollywood Regency-inspired” expansion of this standard tract home with a dramatic pool (c’mon with that swim-up bar INTO the living room?🍹💦🤯), custom finishes, and massive glass pocket doors that when open, create a seamless indoor / outdoor experience. 

It’s available right now via @naturalretreats—Would you wanna live here?!

So what are our thoughts on AI? My IG updated over the weekend with their new AI feature and I actually think it’s pretty cool!

As a photographer, I totally, totally get the fear behind it all as we move forward into a world of content that blurs the lines between fantasy and reality, but I think there’s something to be said for transparency in creativity too.

I know I’ve always been one to pull back that curtain with you guys when it comes to playing around with photoshop and AI in editing, as the possibilities are seemingly endless. I think as long as stuff is disclosed, it can be a lot of fun. Why wouldn’t I want to see what my kid hanging off my shoulder in front of a festive holiday scene looks like?! It beats a closed bagel shop facade tbh. 🤷🏻‍♂️
